e variability in subjective judgments necessitates the variability of the notion of truth dependent on a judge or assessor. They investigate the problem of faultless disagreement by investigating differences and similarities between subjective judgments with epistemic modals on the one hand and predicates of personal taste on the other. Importantly, they also draw on data beyond taste and knowledge, including data from language acquisition. The theoretical analyses are quite diverse. But all proposals are compatible with the contextualist view – that the variability in subjective judgments is an effect of how the meaning of an expression is understood. The volume is relevant for linguists and philosophers of language interested in the problem of faultless disagreement and the semantics and pragmatics of modals and adjectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aInterpersonal communication. 0aLanguage and culture. 0aSapir-Whorf hypothesis. 0aSemanticsxPsychological aspects. 0aSubjectivity (Linguistics) 4aBeurteilung. 4aJudgement. 4aModal Verbs. 4aModalverben. 4aSemantics. 4aSemantik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aMeier, Cécile, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avan Wijnbergen-Huitink, Janneke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2016z9783110485257oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831104021170 cprintz978311037472840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311040200140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110402001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783